# Project Design Canvas — {{PROJECT_NAME}}

A user-centered design canvas for {{PROJECT_NAME}}, in the spirit of the [U.S. Digital Services Playbook](https://playbook.cio.gov/) — start by understanding the people you serve, and let their needs drive what gets built. Fill each prompt briefly and honestly; an empty or hand-waved block is a signal to do more discovery before building. This is a planning artifact: revisit it as you learn, and record the decisions it produces in `decision-log.md`.

## Who the users are and their needs

Name the actual people this serves — the design partners doing the work and the beneficiaries they answer to, kept distinct rather than blurred into a generic "the public." For each, state the need in their words and how you know it (interviews, observation, data), not how you assume it.

## The problem and why now

State the problem from the users' point of view and what makes it worth solving now — the trigger, the cost of the status quo, the window of opportunity. Keep it legible to someone with none of the project's context.

## Intended outcomes & success metrics

Describe the change you intend to produce for those users, and the specific, measurable signals that would tell you it is working. Prefer outcome measures (did the need get met?) over output measures (did we ship the thing?).

## The whole experience

Map the experience end to end, across every touchpoint — online and offline — a user passes through: the steps before, during, and after they interact with what you build. Designing only the digital slice and ignoring the surrounding human process is how good software still fails its users.

## MVP and iteration plan

Define the smallest thing you can put in front of real users to learn whether you are on the right track — the minimum viable product — and the plan for iterating on it: what you will measure, how you will gather feedback, and how that feedback changes the next build. Plan to ship small and improve, not to launch big once.

## Default to open

State this project's commitment to working in the open: what will be public (code, data, documentation, decisions) and under what licenses (see `LICENSE-NOTE.md`), and name anything that must stay closed and why (e.g. sensitive data under `docs/governance/GOVERNANCE.md`). Default to open so the work is reusable, contestable, and accountable; treat closure as the deliberate, documented exception rather than the unexamined default.
